Expand dataset to 7 competitions, retrain models, refresh dashboard

- Add FIFA World Cup 2022, UEFA Women's Euro 2022, Africa Cup of Nations 2023,
  and Copa America 2024 to the existing World Cup 2018 / Women's World Cup 2019
  / Euro 2020 dataset: 8,718 shots across 346 matches (up from 4,309/167).
- Fix competition disambiguation: StatsBomb reuses the same competition_name
  for World Cup 2018 and 2022, so extract_shots.py now also records
  season_name to tell them apart.
- Retrain logistic regression and gradient boosting on the larger dataset;
  held-out test AUC improves to 0.821 (logreg) / 0.816 (gboost) vs.
  StatsBomb's own 0.838 reference. The logreg-over-gboost edge narrows from
  95.9% to 77.9% of bootstrap resamples with more data - reported honestly.
- Feature importance shifts with more data: raw distance now dominates
  decisively, more than in the smaller dataset.
- Regenerate all plots, leaderboards, and per-player shot maps for the 7
  competitions; new standout findings include Brazil's -9.67 xG differential,
  Mbappe's 2022 World Cup run (+4.24), and Alexandra Popp's Women's Euro 2022
  efficiency (+4.08 from 16 shots).
- Add src/generate_dashboard_data.py as the canonical script producing all
  dashboard-facing JSON files (leaderboards, shot samples, player shot maps,
  calculator coefficients) from the trained model.
- Rebuild docs/index.html: 7-competition filter, updated metrics and
  narrative throughout, plus a visual refresh (Space Grotesk/Inter type,
  animated hero, scroll-reveal sections, nav scrollspy, radial xG dial,
  expanded flag map for the new teams).
- Remove obsolete scratch files (_stage*.py training scripts, unused data
  JSON leftovers) now that train_xg_model.py and generate_dashboard_data.py
  cover the full pipeline.
- Update README with the new dataset, results, and file layout.
